    <h2 id="what-are-radicals">What Are Radicals?</h2>
    <p>Chinese characters are not random collections of strokes — they are built from recurring components called <strong>radicals</strong> (部首, bùshǒu). Think of radicals as the "building blocks" or "DNA" of Chinese characters. Just as English words are built from roots and affixes (un-help-ful), Chinese characters combine radicals to create meaning.</p>
    <p>Every Chinese character can be categorized under one radical, which is how characters are organized in traditional dictionaries. There are 214 radicals in the classic Kangxi Dictionary system, ranging from one-stroke radicals like 一 (horizontal line) to complex ones with 17 strokes.</p>

    <h2 id="how-radicals-help">How Radicals Help You Learn</h2>
    <p><strong>Meaning clues:</strong> The semantic radical in a character often indicates its general meaning category. For example, every character containing the water radical (氵) relates to water or liquids in some way: 河 (river), 海 (ocean), 洗 (wash), 游 (swim), 汤 (soup).</p>
    <p><strong>Character decomposition:</strong> Instead of memorizing a 15-stroke character as one complex shape, you can break it into 2-3 familiar radicals. This dramatically reduces the memory burden.</p>
    <p><strong>Dictionary skills:</strong> Knowing radicals lets you look up unfamiliar characters in dictionaries organized by radical (which is still how many Chinese dictionaries are structured).</p>
    <p><strong>Pattern recognition:</strong> Once you know radicals, new characters feel less foreign. You start seeing familiar patterns everywhere, making reading less intimidating.</p>

    <h2 id="top-radicals">The Most Useful Radicals</h2>
    <p>Here are the radicals that appear most frequently in common characters:</p>
    <p><strong>Water (水/氵, shuǐ):</strong> Appears in 河 (river), 海 (sea), 洗 (wash), 游 (swim), 湖 (lake), 汤 (soup). The three-dot form (氵) appears on the left side of characters.</p>
    <p><strong>Heart (心/忄, xīn):</strong> Emotion-related characters: 想 (think), 情 (feeling), 快 (happy/fast), 忙 (busy), 怕 (afraid). The vertical form (忄) appears on the left.</p>
    <p><strong>Hand (手/扌, shǒu):</strong> Action-related characters: 打 (hit), 找 (find), 拿 (take), 推 (push), 拉 (pull).</p>
    <p><strong>Mouth (口, kǒu):</strong> Speech and eating: 吃 (eat), 喝 (drink), 叫 (call), 唱 (sing), 听 (listen).</p>
    <p><strong>Wood (木, mù):</strong> Trees and wooden objects: 树 (tree), 林 (forest), 桌 (table), 椅 (chair).</p>
